Date: Wed 19 May 2004
From: Debora MacKenzie <d.mackenzie@chello.be> [edited]

Your comments on exotic pet diseases on ProMED were most interesting [see
Exotic disease risk, traveling pets - UK 20040519.1332]. I cannot believe
how close some of the observations, reported in the Telegraph, are to
observations that a group in Edinburgh, and others, predicted (and that we
reported and enlarged upon) back in 1998. What I wrote at the time can be
found in the following publications. I can't say we didn't warn them. At
the time, these concerns were largely ignored, except by us.
I would now like to know whether sand flies did jump the Channel, and,
also, what the risk is of kennel-ticks becoming enzootic, with those 2
diseases that they carry.
--
Deborah MacKenzie
New Scientist
<d.mackenzie@chello.be>
[If you can gain access to their archives, the New Scientist articles are:
(1) "Price of pet freedom - Quarantine rules protect Britain from more than
just rabies." New Scientist Vol 157 issue 2117 - 17 Jan 1998, page 14.
(2) Forum : "Mad dogs and Englishmen - Scrap quarantine, but don't drop
your guard, says Debora MacKenzie." New Scientist Vol 157 issue 2121 - 14
Feb 1998, page 48.
I must admit that I didn't pay too much attention to their concerns at the
time. - Mod.MHJ]
