Date: Mon 24 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
[With the help of Colin Hamilton <quaff@dip.demon.co.uk> at QUAFF, I was
able to locate some Defra statistics on dogs and cats entering the UK.
These can be found at:
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/quarantine/pets/procedures/stats.htm>
The numbers of cats recorded entering the UK:
in 2000 (11 months only): 2048
in 2001: 3562
in 2002: 4429
in 2003: 5979
The numbers of dogs entering the UK:
in 2000 (11 months only): 12 501
in 2001: 23 160
in 2002: 36 662
in 2003: 48 593
Taking the summer vacation months of May through Sep inclusively, the
number of dogs entering the UK:
in 2000: 6520
in 2001: 11 545, up 77 percent over 2000
in 2002: 18 829, up 63 percent over 2001
in 2003: 25 060, up 33 percent over 2002
In a few years, the dog numbers will level off.
While these numbers must include non-vacationing animals, and though they
give no idea of the time-density of risk with the vacationing dogs, the
reported perceived number of cases of canine babesiosis indicates a simple
incidence rate of around one to 2 percent of returning dogs. The true
incidence must await proper studies, perhaps, by UK veterinary graduate
students learning something about surveillance. - Mod.MHJ]
